ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, we report a surface engineering route of chlorophyll-derived CDs with amphiphilic PEI via a simple solution-mixing method at room temperature (Scheme 1
                     ). This method has the advantage of the PEI modification significantly enhances the long-term stability of the materials, addressing the stability limitations often observed in earlier methods. Additionally, this approach avoids complex steps or harsh reaction conditions, resulting in a simpler, more scalable, and reproducible synthesis process. Furthermore, as a biocompatible polymer, PEI improves the suitability of the materials for potential biomedical applications, circumventing the drawbacks associated with the use of toxic reagents or surfactants. PEI-MCDs composite in aqueous solution show a narrow-band emission peak at 670 nm with a QY of 45.4 %, which is higher than that of most reported red CDs (3–30 %, seen Table 1
                     ). The mechanism of lipophilic-hydrophilic transformation and emission recovery in aqueous solution is confirmed to be the amphiphilicity shell of PEI on MCDs, which effectively improves the dispersity and suppresses the occurrence of aggregation-caused quenching. Benefiting from this unique feature, PEI-MCDs composite were used as the fluorescent probes for discriminative visualization of lysosomes in various kinds of cells (4T1, CT26, Hela and MDCK). Based on the excellent performance of PEI-MCDs in cell imaging, they were further applied to in vivo imaging studies in zebrafish embryos and larvae. To the best of our knowledge, such hydrophilic CDs with high-efficient narrow-band emission have not been reported yet. Due to its collective properties, PEI-MCDs can be used as a deep-red bio-imaging probe with high brightness, good sensitivity and satisfactory practicability.
